Applying this distinction to our context, we can envision prior outcomes that fall into four categories: a gain (e.g., Mr. A won $100), a non-gain (Mr. A did not win $100), a non-loss (Mr. A did not lose $100), and a loss (Mr. A lost $100) (cells A, B, C, and D in Table 1
). Each of these outcomes has affect associated with it—positive for the favorable outcome cells A and C, and negative for the unfavorable outcome cells B and D.
4 Our question revolves around whether the valence of prior outcomes (positive vs. negative) influences expectations differently depending on whether those outcomes occur in the domain of losses or gains.
